I think calls to `calculateLength` should be avoided before they are needed. Since it&#39;s a private method it can be called when the need arises, not every time the start/end change. This applies to both the `setStart` and `init` methods. So the answer is, yes, it is a violation, and not the only one. An example with a single call to the length might not need the calculation method at all:

    class Line {
    
      private Point start;
      private Point end;
    
      public Line(Point start, Point end) {
        this.start = start;
        this.end = end;
      }
    
      void setStart(Point p) { 
        this.start = p; 
      }

      double getLength() {
        return start.distanceTo(end);
      }
    }

Would examples with more calls need a pre-calculated value? Unless it&#39;s called a million times, maybe not. So the length attribute is also unnecessary.

