answers.body_markdown:
You&#39;re attempting to pass arguments to a `mock` which doesn&#39;t work.

If you want to pass a `mock` of `IAccountService` to your `Controller` in the unit test you could do the following:

    [Fact]
        public async Task RegisterSimpleTest()
        {
            // Arrange
            var mockService = new Mock&lt;IAccountService&gt;();
            mockService.Setup(mock =&gt; mock.EmailRegisterAsync( // all you need to mock goes here)

            var controller = new AccountController(mockService.Object);
            var data = new EmailRegisterViewModel()
            {
                Email = &quot;a@a.a&quot;,
                Password = &quot;123456&quot;,
                ConfirmPassword = &quot;123456&quot;
            };
            // Act
            var result = await controller.Register(data) as ObjectResult;

            // Assert
            Assert.NotNull(result);
            Assert.Equal(200, result.StatusCode);
        }

Consult the [quickstart][1] for info on how to `mock` behaviour.

Also, I would advise *against* setting up your `mock`s in one class and using that everywhere. You need the flexibility to change behaviour of your `mock`s *per test*. If you find setup cumbersome you could look into [AutoFixture.AutoMoq][2] which lets you setup only the dependencies you need to specify behaviour for in a specific test. 


  [1]: https://github.com/Moq/moq4/wiki/Quickstart
  [2]: https://www.nuget.org/packages/AutoFixture.AutoMoq

